BAMRU Members Only -

Interviewing is an important part of search investigation and yet is often a hastily done and incomplete task. In many searches especially in an urban environment, an interview may be the largest generator of clues on where to search. This presentation/workshop will discuss why we need to interview and compare and contrast interview and interrogation in law enforcement and the unique requirements and needs in the Search and Rescue world. It will probe the "how to" mechanics of conducting a good interview from the setting for the interview, to the demeanor of the interviewer, to the type of in depth questions and how the information gathered can be used to paint a mental picture and profile of the missing subject. This information can then be used to assist the planning function in establishing where to look and the best use of SAR resources. The discussions will include initial and post search interviewing, as well as telephone and door-to-door interviewing. The workshop will also include interview practice exercises.

[Leaders: Seffens] 
See:  http://www.smcsheriff.com/communities-we-serve/community-activities/star-camp for details of what STAR camp is.
 
We have performed this presentation for the past 4 years.  By performing this community service, we will be educating kids at the beginning of a week long event.  For many of these kids, it is the first time camping in a wilderness setting.  We equip the kids with some knowledge about how help themselves and us in the event they become lost in the wilderness.  Consider it "Preventative SAR".
 
We typically show a 15 minute video, and have a short Q&A about what they learned.  Afterwards, we take the group outside and let the groups perform some little handling exercises where they get a feeling for what it's like to be involved in a rescue and that it's hard work; hopefully it makes it a bit fun, and perhaps they might remember some of the presentation.
 
Members are encouraged to attend and assist with the presentation and supervise the litter handling.  Having members in red shirts or SMCSO uniforms are appreciated.

(BE2060 - 18f6f360d5dfd1f27c8b94a2d706d14e)

[Leaders: Chris Young] Interviewing is an important part of search investigation and yet is often a hastily done and incomplete task. In many searches especially in an urban environment, an interview may be the largest generator of clues on where to search. This presentation/workshop will discuss why we need to interview and compare and contrast interview and interrogation in law enforcement and the unique requirements and needs in the Search and Rescue world. It will probe the "how to" mechanics of conducting a good interview from the setting for the interview, to the demeanor of the interviewer, to the type of in depth questions and how the information gathered can be used to paint a mental picture and profile of the missing subject. This information can then be used to assist the planning function in establishing where to look and the best use of SAR resources. The discussions will include initial and post search interviewing, as well as telephone and door-to-door interviewing. The workshop will also include interview practice exercises.
